Bin the continuous values into discrete intervals¶

In [10]:
#https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.cut.html
#Bin the continuous values into discrete intervals.
#labels for age
age_labels = ['0-10', '11-20', '21-30', '31-40', '41-50', '51-60', '61-70', '71-80']
#use pandas cut to bin the continuous variable age
titanic_df['age_group'] = pd.cut(titanic_df.Age, range(0, 81, 10), labels=age_labels)
titanic_df.tail(5) #show the last five rows

[Bar plot] Distribution of Pclass in percentage¶

  • Create a bar plot using pandas .plot with kind="bar" in orange color.
  • Create the grid with a grid style as below.
  • Do not forget to add all the details (e.g., title, labels, grid, description, legends if any).
In [13]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
ax = (titanic_df.Pclass.value_counts().sort_index()/len(titanic_df)).plot(kind='bar',  legend=True, color='orange')
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(round(p.get_height(), 2), (p.get_x() * 1.005 + 0.25, p.get_height() * 1.005 + 0.004), ha='center', weight='bold', size=12)
ax.grid(b=True, which='major', color='gray')
plt.title("Distribution of Pclass", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Pclass", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Percentage (%)", fontsize=14)
plt.show()

[Bar plot] Which Pclass had a better chance of survival?¶

  • Use color 'green' for survivors and 'tab:olive' for non-survivors. Choose your own style for the grid.
  • Use plt.bar(). Create stacked bar charts, vertical, with counts on y-axis.
  • Use plt.bar(). Create stacked bar charts, horizontal, with percentage of survival rate on x-axis.
  • Use Seaborn displot(). Create stacked bar charts, vertical, with counts on y-axis.
  • Use Seaborn. Create grouped bar charts, horizontal, with "percentage on x-axis of survival rates". No need to display non-survivors but the grouped bar charts display gender. Use color to distinguish gender.
  • Do not forget to add all the details (e.g., title, labels, grid, description, legends if any).
In [14]:
#Use plt.bar(). Create stacked bar charts, vertical, with counts on y-axis.
pclass_survived=titanic_df.groupby(["Pclass", "Survived"]).size()
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,4))
ax.bar("1",pclass_survived[1][0],  width=0.4, label='Non-Survivors', color='olive')
ax.bar("1", pclass_survived[1][1],  width=0.4, bottom=pclass_survived[1][0], label='Survivors', color='green')
ax.bar("2", pclass_survived[2][0],  width=0.4, color='olive')
ax.bar("2", pclass_survived[2][1],  width=0.4, bottom=pclass_survived[2][0], color='green')
ax.bar("3", pclass_survived[3][0],  width=0.4, color='olive')
ax.bar("3", pclass_survived[3][1],  width=0.4, bottom=pclass_survived[3][0], color='green')
#putting pclass count with survived with negative offset
y_offset = -30
#adding label to each patch
for bar in ax.patches:
    ax.text(
      bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2,
      bar.get_height() + bar.get_y() + y_offset,
      # actual value to show.
      round(bar.get_height()),
      # Center the labels and style them a bit.
      ha='center', color='w', weight='bold', size=12
    )
ax.legend()
ax.grid(b=True, which='major', color='gray')
plt.title("Pclass had better chance of survival", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Pclass", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=14)
sb.set_style("darkgrid")
plt.show()

# Use plt.bar(). Create stacked bar charts, horizontal, with percentage of survival rate on x-axis.
pclass_survived_per=(titanic_df.groupby(["Pclass", "Survived"])["Pclass"].count()/titanic_df.groupby(['Pclass'])['Pclass'].size())* 100
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize= (8, 5))
ax.barh(1, width= pclass_survived_per[1][0],  label='Non-Survivors', color='olive')
ax.barh(1, width= pclass_survived_per[1][1], left=pclass_survived_per[1][0], label='Survivors', color='green')
ax.barh(2, width= pclass_survived_per[2][0], color='olive')
ax.barh(2, width= pclass_survived_per[2][1], left=pclass_survived_per[2][0], color='green')
ax.barh(3, width= pclass_survived_per[3][0], color='olive')
ax.barh(3,width= pclass_survived_per[3][1], left=pclass_survived_per[3][0], color='green')

for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(round(p.get_width(), 2), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() - 15 , p.get_height() + p.get_y() - 0.45), ha='center', color='w', weight='bold', size=14)
ax.grid(b=True, which='major', color='gray')

ax.legend()
ax.grid(b=True, which='major', color='gray')
plt.title("Pclass had better chance of survival", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Percentage of survival rate", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Pclass", fontsize=14)
plt.show()

plt.grid(b=True, which='major', color='gray')
plt.ylabel("Percentage of Survival Rates", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Pclass", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Percentage of Survival Rates", fontsize=14)
plt.show()

[Pie plot] Distribution of Pclass in percentage.¶

  • Use 3 different colors to color the pie plot for the three Pclasses.
  • Start the pie start angle from 0 degrees.
  • Round to two decimal places to show percentage numbers and add '%' after the number.
  • Use the 'explode' parameter to distinguish the largest distribution of Pclass.

# Since Siblings/Spouses Aboard includes zero values, size zero needs to be visible when plotting
ssSize = np.array(titanic_df['Siblings/Spouses Aboard']) 
ssSize = (ssSize + 1)

# Q10> Write your code here. 
fig = px.scatter_3d(titanic_df, x='Gender', y='Age', z='Survived', 
              color='Survived', size=ssSize, size_max=30,
              symbol='Pclass', opacity=0.8,
              hover_data=['Fare','Parents/Children Aboard'],
              color_continuous_scale='Portland')



fig.for_each_trace(
    lambda trace: trace.update(marker_symbol="diamond") if trace.name == "1" else (),
)

fig.update_traces(marker=dict(line=dict(width=1,
                                        color='black')),
                  selector=dict(mode='markers'))

mytitle = "" #"Title of this 3D"
fig.update_layout(
    title={
        'text': mytitle,
        'y':0.9,
        'x':0.5,
        'xanchor': 'center',
        'yanchor': 'top'},
    margin=dict(l=0, r=0, b=0, t=0),
    legend=dict(
        yanchor="top",
        y=0.99,
        xanchor="left",
        x=0.01
))

fig.show()
